                <p/>
            </div> 
            <div type="translation">
                <lg met="iambic">
                   <l n="1">Niko, the lawful wife of Archon. But Hades</l>
               	<l n="2">carries her off, having made no assessment of her for ill or for virtue.</l>
               	<l n="3">Her husband, with his own hands, placed her here,</l>
               	<l n="4">his prudent and irreproachable wife,</l>
               	<l n="5">the Kretan daughter of Aristokrates - a double pain, that this was</l>
               	<l n="6">before his pious wife bore him any noble children.</l> 
               	<l n="7">May another, with better fortune, marry a girl like her,</l>
               	<l n="8">who understands how to keep his household safe from harm</l>
                </lg>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>An early or mid-third century date would be appropriate for the lettering of this epigram marking the death in childbirth of Niko which Fraser (Ptol. Alex. I, 613) described as ‘conventional and of no great merit’ for its diffuseness.</p> 
            </div>
